{"key":"post-9517835","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9517835</id>\n<content>If you're going to build a flowhood, check out &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.fungifun.org/English/Flowhood&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;Anno's site&lt;/a&gt; first.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I have used the series 1 from FP for many years on the same filter.&amp;nbsp; Simply duct tape a furnace filter over the air intake and your expensive hepa will last nearly forever.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Laminar flow is straight line airflow.&amp;nbsp; It means when the sterile air hits your hands and tools, it will flow along and around them without creating eddys or other turbulent currents.&amp;nbsp; The 'lighter test' is done by holding the lighter at all places within the flow area.&amp;nbsp; You should see the flame bend but not go out, and it should bend straight over, not flickering from side to side.&amp;nbsp; The intensity of the flow should be the same, and the flame should not bend more at one part of the work area than another.&amp;nbsp; Laminar flow is achieved by creating pressure in a plenum behind the filter.&amp;nbsp; By having an even pressure &lt;i&gt;behind&lt;/i&gt; the filter, the flow through and out the other side is the same everywhere.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9521335</next>\n<prev>9517761</prev>\n<first>9515407</first>\n<last>9521375</last>\n<when>1230665314</when>\n<utime>12/30/08 09:28 PM</utime>\n</post>"}